HEADWORD: Apophyge
<hw>A*poph"y*ge</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr.
<grk>'apofygh`</grk> escape, in arch. the curve with which the shaft
escapes into its base or capital, fr. <grk>'apofey`gein</grk> to flee
away; <grk>'apo`</grk> from + <grk>fey`gein</grk> to flee: cf. F.
<ets>apophyge</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>The small hollow
curvature given to the top or bottom of the shaft of a column where it
expands to meet the edge of the fillet; -- called also the
<altname>scape</altname>.</def> <rj><au>Parker.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Apophyllite</ent>⟦br⟧
